choices.text: easily the 1973 oil shock. Both France with 30 million people and the UK with 49 million were suddenly deprived of 3/5 of their oil. All of this reminds me of several of Mahdi Darius Nazemroayas's articles of that time; specifically they are links 365, 368, 540, 689, 713, 723: this was at the time of Nixon, who had closed the gold window, who prevented the Bretton Woods Agreement from leading to higher wages in developed countries as planned, and when the capitalists knew of the coming "stagflation"/higher inflation, i.e. higher income for all but also increased costs. The author describes the crisis and the to-be-implemented austerity measures not as complex, but actually simple enough to read in simple English. When speaking of the situation itself, he left his commentaries on Thatcherism to the British. However, his article of 538 will be quoted here, because he also describes events that are similar to Germany: "The Quadragesima Anno de Pio XI admonished capitalists to raise the wage of workers; Britain adopted the exact opposite policy in 1971 and France carried out the greatest raise in wages in 1936 and 1946, but did so with great difficulties; Thatcher's New Right openly brandishes neoconservatism and promises to annihilate all unions."
